      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-15T18:40:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Certainly this shouldn’t be defined on non-x86-family. But should this even be defined on non-x86_64? The intent would be to allow a 32-bit process to get and set a 64-bit lightweight process’ %fs/%gs base address. But I don’t think that this is actually possible.\n\nlinux-4.9.28/arch/x86/kernel/ptrace.c compat_arch_ptrace() delegates to ia32_arch_ptrace(), which doesn’t understand PTRACE_ARCH_PRCTL. So I don’t think that this makes sense for a 32-bit x86 user program, even when expecting to run on an x86_64 kernel. (kernel/ptrace.c uses compat_arch_ptrace() instead of arch_ptrace() in the “compat” version of the ptrace() system call.)\n\nLooking at the NDK, it appears that PTRACE_ARCH_PRCTL should always be available when targeting x86_64 at any API level that supports x86_64. On that basis, I don’t think that we need this at all.",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
